Author: pennypanda.
Content: Guys are you aware of the Reality.eth module exploit? My team has discovered it being able to drain funds from safes using iy

Author: mikhailmv
Content: if you're talknig about this https://hackmd.io/g0txop3tTfGxcNKxn4z4Jg?view then yes we're aware

Author: mikhailmv
Content: as it is highlighted in the article is not really a module exploit but a lack of monitoring and attention

Author: mikhailmv
Content: and just to clarify we don't maintain the reality.eth module, it is maintained by https://www.gnosisguild.org/

Author: pennypanda.
Content: I've been in conversation with Lukas about this for a while today

Author: pennypanda.
Content:
This is not simply a case of not paying attention ser.
An attacker was able to bypass an entire Snapshot voting system, create (spoof?) a proposal on their own that used a proposal_id already used once in the past by the DAO. Then set a very short amount of time period, and pass it on their own

Author: pennypanda.
Content: It's a Storage Collision Attack at the contract level

Author: pennypanda.
Content: An outsider being able to access funds inside a safe, while not being an owner of the safe, not being an eligible voter in Snapshot either

Author: pennypanda.
Content: Update: the Storage Collision doesn't affect the Reality Contracts, only fake swaps that the attacker had created.

Author: pennypanda.
Content: They were able to put malicious txn instructions in the eip712 hash, since the reality module just passed it, the Gnosis safe also passed the txn, which included token approval and transfer functions and the attacker was able to swipe the funds

Author: swnt
Content:
I hope this is the correct channel to ask. Regarding the massive distributed hacks and wallet drains happening currently (https://www.reddit.com/r/CryptoCurrency/comments/12s45c5/an_update_on_the_crypto_hack_currently_taking/). **Does anybody know, if Safe Smart Contract multi-sig wallets also have been drained?** I've only limited amounts of money there, so I've not been pwned currently. Or perhaps the hackers haven't implemented that.

On that regard, would it be possible to actually implement a variation of Gnosis Safes, where the owners are NOT publicly visible? (https://etherscan.io/address/0xE0a88c4E543a0e0d15d697403849A75Da40962B4#readProxyContract). Such a feature could provide interesting privacy guarantees and at the same time it could also shield the above attack, because the attacker would need to know which owners are used and cannot simply look them up on chain. Obviously this has drawbacks in case one forgets some of the owners, but nevertheless, it's interesting.

Author: bing2
Content: No. Also, Safes are smart contract wallets, unlike those described in the article. Depending on the policy you set, having one owner wallet compromised will not immediately give access to the scammer/hacker.

Author: swnt
Content:
Indeed. Enough signers need to be compromised to hack the gnosis safe. I am asking whether perhaps the hacker didn't brother implementing this for gnosis safes, since going for EOAs was already lucrative.

It's funny that months ago I decided for a gnosis safe instead of a hardware wallet - because I didn't like the *existence* of a single point of failure - the seed phrase. Maybe that's what has protected me until now with this current hack ^^'
